children.comment: A stack trace, comprised of a list of stack frames.
children.name: Trace

children.comment:
Returns a human-readable representation of [stackTrace]. If [terse] is
set, this folds together multiple stack frames from the Dart core
libraries, so that only the core library method directly called from user
code is visible (see [Trace.terse]).
children.name: format

children.comment:
Returns a new [Trace] based on [this] where multiple stack frames matching
[predicate] are folded together. This means that whenever there are
multiple frames in a row that match [predicate], only the last one is
kept.

This is useful for limiting the amount of library code that appears in a
stack trace by only showing user code and code that's called by user code.
children.name: foldFrames

children.comment: Returns a human-readable string representation of [this].
children.name: toString

children.comment:
Returns a VM-style [StackTrace] object.

The return value's [toString] method will always return a string
representation in the Dart VM's stack trace format, regardless of what
platform is being used.
children.name: vmTrace

children.comment:
Returns a terser version of [this].

This is accomplished by folding together multiple stack frames from the
core library, as in [foldFrames]. Remaining core library frames have their
libraries, "-patch" suffixes, and line numbers removed.
children.name: terse

children.comment: The stack frames that comprise this stack trace.
children.name: frames

children.comment:
Returns the current stack trace.

By default, the first frame of this trace will be the line where
[Trace.current] is called. If [level] is passed, the trace will start that
many frames up instead.
children.name: current

children.comment:
Returns a new stack trace containing the same data as [trace].

If [trace] is a native [StackTrace], its data will be parsed out; if it's
a [Trace], it will be returned as-is.
children.name: from

children.comment:
Parses a string representation of a stack trace.

[trace] should be formatted in the same way as a Dart VM or browser stack
trace.
children.name: parse

children.comment: Parses a string representation of a Dart VM stack trace.
children.name: parseVM

children.comment: Parses a string representation of a Chrome/V8 stack trace.
children.name: parseV8

children.comment: Parses a string representation of a Firefox stack trace.
children.name: parseFirefox

children.comment: Parses this package's a string representation of a stack trace.
children.name: parseFriendly

children.comment: Returns a new [Trace] comprised of [frames].

An interface implemented by all stack trace objects.

A [StackTrace] is intended to convey information to the user about the call
sequence that triggered an exception.

These objects are created by the runtime, it is not possible to create
them programmatically.
children.name: StackTrace

children.comment:
Returns a [String] representation of the stack trace.

The string represents the full stack trace starting from
the point where a throw ocurred to the top of the current call sequence.

The exact format of the string representation is not final.
children.name: toString

children.comment: Everything in Dart is an [Object].
children.name: Object

children.comment:
The equality operator.

The default behavior for all [Object]s is to return true if and
only if [:this:] and [other] are the same object.

If a subclass overrides the equality operator it should override
the [hashCode] method as well to maintain consistency.
Returns a string representation of this object.
children.name: toString

children.comment:
[noSuchMethod] is invoked when users invoke a non-existant method
on an object. The name of the method and the arguments of the
invocation are passed to [noSuchMethod] in an [Invocation].
If [noSuchMethod] returns a value, that value becomes the result of
the original invocation.

The default behavior of [noSuchMethod] is to throw a
[noSuchMethodError].
children.name: noSuchMethod

children.comment:
Get a hash code for this object.

All objects have hash codes. Hash codes are guaranteed to be the
same for objects that are equal when compared using the equality
operator [:==:]. Other than that there are no guarantees about
the hash codes. They will not be consistent between runs and
there are no distribution guarantees.

If a subclass overrides [hashCode] it should override the
equality operator as well to maintain consistency.
children.name: hashCode

children.comment: A representation of the runtime type of the object.
children.name: runtimeType

children.comment:
Creates a new [Object] instance.

[Object] instances have no meaningful state, and are only useful
through their identity. An [Object] instance is equal to itself
only.

A wrapper around a [TraceThunk]. This works around issue 9579 by avoiding
the conversion of native [StackTrace]s to strings until it's absolutely
necessary.
children.name: LazyTrace

children.comment: A thunk for lazily constructing a [Trace].
children.name: TraceThunk
